  footnotes: []
english:
  title: Ceremonial Text in Honor of Record-Keeper Lee Wi-ryang, Composed on Behalf of Dam Ji
  author: Lim Chun
  language: eng
  text: |-
    The preferences of mankind run contrary to Heaven's will.
    It grants misfortune to the virtuous and blessing to the wicked,
    Lets tyrants live long while the wise perish young.
    Those the world scorns together—Heaven grants them years;
    Those we all wish to flourish—even a moment's grace is denied.
    Who then holds the power of such dispensation?

    Your death stirs only deeper resentment toward that cold Heaven.
    I think of your brilliant spirit, your flowing beard and broad brow,
    A courage vast as the world itself.
    You possessed such depth of character from birth,
    And in the spring of your years, with fortune at your side,
    All your companions looked to see you rise.

    I knew you in my youth among our peers.
    Though younger than I in years, your vigor burned bright—
    Yet one day you lay down and suddenly departed,
    Leaving me behind.

    The evening I learned of your passing,
    I felt as though I myself had died.
    Food turned to ash within my throat,
    And sorrow filled my heart.

    The bonds of righteousness between us run deep as yellow earth,
    Yet how shall we meet again to laugh and talk, to clap hands in joy?
    When later I raise a cup to drink, I shall surely think of you.
    As duty calls me to distant lands and I cannot attend your grave,
    I offer this single cup of wine—
    Come and receive it, and do not forget me.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: Liu Chang (劉昶) appears to be a reference invoking the memory of another esteemed figure, emphasizing how the deceased will be remembered alongside worthy souls of the past.
  - key: ''
    value: The 'yellow earth' (황천/黃泉) refers to the underworld or afterlife in classical East Asian thought, suggesting the permanence of their spiritual bond.
  - key: ''
    value: '''Record-keeper'' (록사/錄事) was an administrative position in medieval Korean government.'
  - key: ''
    value: The speaker mentions being sent on a distant mission, preventing attendance at the funeral rites—a significant sorrow in the context of traditional funerary practices.
